metadata.title: How to Pass Tier 1 & 2 Selections Part 1/3: Difference Between Tier 1 & 2
metadata.description:
📌 Part 1 of 3: The Difference Between Tier 1 and Tier 2 Units – How to Pass Special Operations Selections

Welcome to Part 1 of my three-part series on how to pass Tier 1 and Tier 2 selections in U.S. Special Operations.

Before you can even think about surviving selection, you need to understand what you're preparing for. Too many people say they want to go “Tier 1” without knowing what that even means. This video is all about laying out the real differences between Tier 1 and Tier 2 units, so you know exactly what you’re getting into—and why it matters.

🔎 What’s the difference?
Tier 2 units are elite, but they’re designed for broader special operations missions. These include:
✅ Army Special Forces (Green Berets)
✅ 75th Ranger Regiment
✅ Navy SEAL Teams
✅ Marine Raiders (MARSOC)
✅ Air Force Special Tactics

These units train hard, deploy constantly, and often work in small teams advising partners, conducting raids, or preparing the battlespace for larger missions.

Tier 1 units, on the other hand, are the nation’s most secretive, specialized, and capable counterterror and hostage rescue forces:
✅ Delta Force (CAG)
✅ SEAL Team 6 (DEVGRU)
✅ Intelligence Support Activity 

Their selection is even more grueling, and their training pipelines are longer, with a focus on direct action, surgical strikes, and high-value target capture or kill missions. These units are given priority funding, access to cutting-edge technology, and often work with the highest-level intelligence to conduct missions that other units simply can’t.

⚡ Why is this important?
Because your preparation must match your target. Tier 2 selections test your ability to operate in small teams, endure physically demanding tasks, and show leadership under stress. Tier 1 selections go further—they strip away the team support and evaluate you as an individual problem-solver under relentless pressure.

If you don't understand these differences, you'll train for the wrong fight.

👊 Coming Up Next:
Part 2 – How to Pass Tier 2 Selections
Part 3 – How to Pass Tier 1 Selections

If you have questions, thoughts, or your own experiences, drop them in the comments—I read everything. And make sure you subscribe so you don’t miss the next parts of this series.

Thanks for watching—and train smart.

key_points.text: This briefing is Part 1 of a three-part series on how to pass Tier 1 and Tier 2 selections.
Part 1 specifically covers the distinctions between Tier 1 and Tier 2 units and their selection processes.
The speaker is a former Special Forces and Tier 1 operator, providing an insider's perspective.
The speaker had the privilege to serve as a cadre/instructor for a Tier 1 selection.
The speaker's role as cadre/instructor began approximately four years after he successfully passed selection.
Common colloquialisms in special operations include 'White SOF' and 'Black SOF'.
'White SOF' refers to Tier 2 units.
Tier 2 units include Rangers, Special Forces, MARSOC Raiders, Marine Force Recon, and most SEAL teams.
Most SEALs, excluding SEAL Team 6, are commonly referred to as 'JV SEALs' or 'White side SEALs'.
'Black SOF' refers to Tier 1 units.
SEAL Team 6 (DevGru) is a distinct organization, approximately five times larger than any other individual SEAL team.
SEAL Team 6 has an estimated three to four times more operators than other SEAL teams.
SEAL Team 6 employs five to ten times more support staff compared to other SEAL teams.
The three primary operational Tier 1 units are Delta Force, DevGru (SEAL Team 6), and the Intelligence Support Activity (ISA).
These Tier 1 units' organizational structures are designed after the British SAS, utilizing squadrons and troops.
Adjacent units, such as the 24th STS (Air Force Special Operations), provide support to both Tier 1 and Tier 2 elements.
The 24th STS includes roles like J TACS, TACPs, and Pararescue.
The speaker has experience serving alongside J TACS in both Tier 2 and Tier 1 contexts.
The speaker expressed uncertainty regarding the 24th STS's internal process for assigning personnel to Tier 1 versus Tier 2 support roles.
A key distinction between Tier 2 and Tier 1 selections lies in their approach to psychological pressure and team dynamics.
Tier 2 selections are characterized by negative reinforcement, including yelling, screaming, and direct attempts to mentally break candidates.
Tier 2 selections incorporate a significant number of team-oriented events.
Tier 1 selections do not utilize yelling or any form of negative reinforcement.
Tier 1 selections also deliberately withhold positive reinforcement.
Events in Tier 1 selections are almost entirely individual, with very few to no team-based challenges.
Another common colloquialism differentiates 'assaulters' or 'operators' from 'support personnel' within these units.
Assaulters or operators are the frontline personnel, responsible for primary ground operations, particularly in Tier 1 units like SEAL Team 6 or Delta.
All other roles within these units are generally classified as support personnel.
Task Force colors were a colloquialism used in the early 2000s, extending into the mid-2000s, to identify Tier 1 personnel.
These Task Force colors are still occasionally used to identify Tier 1 elements when not in uniform or in inter-agency meetings.
Delta Force's designated Task Force color is Green.
SEAL Team 6's designated Task Force color is Blue.
The Intelligence Support Activity's (ISA) designated Task Force color is Orange, also known as TFO.
Part 2 of the series will be released next, focusing on how Tier 2 selections are generally conducted.
Part 2 will provide essential information and advice to help candidates pass a Tier 2 selection.
Part 3 of the series will cover Tier 1 selections, detailing their unique differences.
Part 3 will offer the speaker's best advice and strategies for passing Tier 1 selections.
The speaker emphasizes that all information provided reflects his personal opinion.

summary:
This briefing constitutes the first part of a three-part series detailing the selection processes for Tier 1 and Tier 2 special operations units. The speaker, a former Special Forces and Tier 1 operator who also served as a cadre/instructor for a Tier 1 selection, provides an insider's perspective on the distinctions between these elite forces.

The presentation differentiates between "White SOF" (Tier 2 units such as Rangers, Special Forces, MARSOC Raiders, Marine Force Recon, and most SEAL teams, commonly referred to as JV SEALs) and "Black SOF" (Tier 1 units, notably Delta Force, DevGru/SEAL Team 6, and the Intelligence Support Activity, with SEAL Team 6 being significantly larger than other SEAL organizations). Adjacent support units like the 24th STS, encompassing J TACS and PJs, are also mentioned for their support to both Tier 1 and Tier 2 elements.

A critical distinction is highlighted in the selection methodologies: Tier 2 selections are characterized by intense negative reinforcement, yelling, and a focus on team-oriented events aimed at mental attrition. Conversely, Tier 1 selections eschew negative or positive reinforcement, focusing almost exclusively on individual performance and psychological assessment. The briefing also clarifies the roles of "assaulters" or "operators" (front-line personnel) versus "support personnel" within these units.

Finally, the speaker introduces historical colloquialisms, such as "Task Force colors" (Green for Delta Force, Blue for SEAL Team 6, and Orange/TFO for the Intelligence Support Activity), used in the early to mid-2000s to identify Tier 1 personnel outside uniform. The subsequent parts of the series are announced, focusing on the specifics of Tier 2 and Tier 1 selection processes.
